WEBVTT

00:01.335 --> 00:03.095
Brianna and I can’t go back
until we know

00:03.170 --> 00:05.670
whether Jemmy
can hear those stones.

00:05.797 --> 00:07.377
As soon as we know
if Jemmy can travel,

00:07.508 --> 00:09.008
<i>we’ll use Bonnet’s gem
to leave.</i>

00:09.092 --> 00:10.842
As you said,
it’s our ticket home.

00:10.928 --> 00:13.008
So if you have
come recruitin’,

00:13.138 --> 00:15.678
you could not have found
any better men
in all the Carolinas.

00:15.807 --> 00:17.727
We’ll ride to Hillsborough
with you.

00:17.851 --> 00:20.601
I hope you didn’t waste any
good medicine on that coward.

00:20.687 --> 00:22.767
Powder burns were on his back.

00:22.856 --> 00:25.026
So whoever shot him,
shot him at close range.

00:25.108 --> 00:26.818
No woman speaks
to me like that.

00:26.902 --> 00:28.782
You can’t give away my money!

00:28.862 --> 00:30.742
[ muffled groaning ]

00:30.864 --> 00:32.374
[ bone snaps ]

00:37.037 --> 00:39.957
[ insects and birds chirping ]

00:42.209 --> 00:44.999
[ wind blows ]

00:48.048 --> 00:49.878
JAMIE: What’s in
those burlap bags?

00:49.967 --> 00:52.547
I dinna recall buying
those in Woolam’s Creek.

00:52.678 --> 00:54.388
Peanuts.

00:54.513 --> 00:56.563
‐ Peanuts?
‐ Mm‐hmm.

00:56.682 --> 00:59.392
Why?
The pigs dinna want for slops.

01:00.352 --> 01:02.272
Or do you, uh,

01:02.396 --> 01:04.226
mean to make medicine
out of them, Sassenach?

01:04.356 --> 01:06.896
No, sandwiches.

01:06.984 --> 01:09.074
Haven’t quite mastered
ice cream yet,

01:09.194 --> 01:10.904
but I’ll be damned
if Jemmy grows up

01:11.029 --> 01:14.409
without tasting peanut butter
and jelly sandwiches.

01:23.375 --> 01:26.545
[ uneasy music ]

01:26.628 --> 01:28.508
[ coughing ]

01:28.589 --> 01:31.469
<i>♪</i>

01:35.721 --> 01:38.261
[ coughing ]

01:39.975 --> 01:42.395
‐ Claire?
‐ [ coughs ]

01:49.109 --> 01:50.779
[ coughs ]

01:53.488 --> 01:55.658
‐ Dead.
‐ Aye, they all are.

01:55.782 --> 01:57.122
Why are they all
in the house?

01:57.200 --> 01:58.870
Why didn’t they run outside
when the fire started?

01:58.952 --> 02:00.372
It’s a bit strange.

02:00.454 --> 02:03.794
Because they were all dead
before the fire started.

02:03.915 --> 02:06.325
I canna tell
what killed them.

02:06.460 --> 02:08.420
There’s another one over here.

02:12.591 --> 02:15.471
<i>♪</i>

02:18.639 --> 02:20.849
I can tell you
how this one died.

02:23.810 --> 02:25.310
‐ BRIANNA: Indians?
<i>‐ JAMIE: Yeah, could be.</i>

02:25.437 --> 02:28.017
Seems unusual.

02:28.148 --> 02:30.648
There’s only one arrow.

02:30.776 --> 02:33.146
<i>Let’s all take a look about.</i>

02:33.236 --> 02:36.356
See if anyone got away
or is hidin’ in the woods.

02:36.490 --> 02:39.330
[ coughs, groans ]

02:40.577 --> 02:42.577
Anyone there?

02:42.663 --> 02:45.623
‐ [ coughs ]
<i>‐ CLAIRE: Is there
anybody out there?</i>

02:45.707 --> 02:49.087
[ faint groaning, whimpering ]

02:52.798 --> 02:56.048
‐ Oh, God.
<i>‐ CLAIRE: Hello?</i>

02:57.010 --> 02:59.850
<i>JAMIE: Is anyone there?
</i> <i>Dinna be afraid.</i>

02:59.971 --> 03:01.681
<i>BRIANNA: Is there
anybody out there?</i>

03:01.765 --> 03:03.475
[ strained breathing ]

03:03.558 --> 03:05.438
<i>JAMIE: It’s safe now.</i>

03:05.519 --> 03:06.899
<i>‐ CLAIRE: We’re here to help.
</i> ‐ ROGER: Jamie.

03:07.020 --> 03:08.810
<i>BRIANNA: Anyone?</i>

03:08.897 --> 03:11.017
<i>Is there?</i>

03:11.149 --> 03:13.899
[ girl breathing raggedly ]

03:14.027 --> 03:17.067
[ somber music ]

03:17.197 --> 03:19.867
<i>♪</i>

03:35.716 --> 03:37.836
[ sighs ]

03:43.390 --> 03:45.140
<i>ROGER: No.</i>

03:45.225 --> 03:47.385
I’ll do it.

03:52.274 --> 03:54.734
[ whimpering ]

03:54.818 --> 03:57.358
It’s gonna be all right,
sweetheart.

04:04.077 --> 04:06.577
[ muffled groaning ]

04:06.663 --> 04:09.003
Thou goest home this night

04:09.082 --> 04:11.252
<i>to thy home of autumn,</i>

04:11.334 --> 04:13.884
<i>and of spring and of summer.</i>

04:13.962 --> 04:16.882
Thou goest home this night

04:16.965 --> 04:19.125
to thy perpetual home,

04:19.259 --> 04:23.259
<i>to thine eternal bed.</i>

04:25.766 --> 04:28.686
To thine eternal slumber.

04:28.769 --> 04:31.939
<i>♪</i>

05:02.177 --> 05:04.297
<i>CHOIR:
♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

05:04.387 --> 05:07.637
<i>♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪</i>

05:07.766 --> 05:09.766
<i>♪ Say, could that lass ♪</i>

05:09.851 --> 05:13.061
<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

05:13.146 --> 05:15.106
<i>♪ Merry of soul ♪</i>

05:15.190 --> 05:18.480
<i>♪ She sailed on a day ♪</i>

05:18.568 --> 05:20.358
<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

05:20.487 --> 05:23.657
<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

05:23.740 --> 05:26.120
<i>♪ Billow and breeze ♪</i>

05:26.201 --> 05:28.831
<i>♪ Islands and seas ♪</i>

05:28.954 --> 05:31.754
<i>♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪</i>

05:31.832 --> 05:34.082
<i>♪ Mountains of rain
</i> <i>and sun ♪</i>

05:34.167 --> 05:36.667
<i>♪ All that was good ♪</i>

05:36.795 --> 05:39.135
<i>♪ All that was fair ♪</i>

05:39.214 --> 05:41.514
<i>♪ All that was me ♪</i>

05:41.591 --> 05:44.471
<i>♪ Is gone ♪</i>

05:44.553 --> 05:46.723
<i>♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

05:46.847 --> 05:49.597
<i>♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪</i>

05:49.683 --> 05:51.683
<i>♪ Say, could that lass ♪</i>

05:51.768 --> 05:54.848
<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

05:54.938 --> 05:56.978
<i>♪ Merry of soul ♪</i>

05:57.065 --> 06:00.025
<i>♪ She sailed on a day ♪</i>

06:00.151 --> 06:03.951
<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

06:04.030 --> 06:10.200
<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

06:10.704 --> 06:13.464
[ dramatic music ]

06:13.540 --> 06:16.040
<i>♪</i>

06:16.126 --> 06:20.046
<i>WOMAN:
♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

06:20.171 --> 06:22.551
<i>♪ Of a lass ♪</i>

06:22.632 --> 06:25.722
<i>♪ That is gone ♪</i>

06:25.844 --> 06:30.564
<i>♪ Say, could that lass ♪</i>

06:30.640 --> 06:32.980
<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

06:33.059 --> 06:36.099
[ laughter ]

06:40.859 --> 06:42.399
<i>CLAIRE: Do you remember</i>

06:42.485 --> 06:45.485
<i>when I left to go back
through the stones?</i>

06:45.572 --> 06:48.032
You made me peanut butter
and jelly sandwiches

06:48.116 --> 06:49.696
to sustain me on my travels.

06:49.784 --> 06:51.584
Mm‐hmm,
just wanted to make sure

06:51.661 --> 06:54.081
you had one last piece of home
wherever you ended up.

06:54.164 --> 06:55.294
<i>YOUNG IAN: Can you take it?</i>

06:55.415 --> 06:57.245
I bet you can take it.
I bet you can.

06:57.334 --> 06:59.424
‐ Ah‐ha!
‐ [ laughs ]

06:59.544 --> 07:02.214
They were the most delicious
things I’ve ever tasted.

07:02.297 --> 07:04.877
‐ I’m glad.
<i>‐ JEMMY: Ouch!</i>

07:04.966 --> 07:06.926
It’s hot.

07:07.052 --> 07:08.762
‐ It’s hot? Huh.
‐ [ blows ]

07:10.388 --> 07:12.768
‐ Do you want it?
‐ No!

07:12.891 --> 07:14.681
No?
But you wanted it a moment ago.

07:14.768 --> 07:17.478
I don’t want it anymore.

07:17.604 --> 07:19.064
[ whimpers softly ]

07:19.147 --> 07:20.567
He’s saying it’s hot?

07:20.649 --> 07:23.729
[ light music ]

07:24.486 --> 07:27.816
‐ It is really warm.
‐ No, it’s not.

07:27.948 --> 07:29.738
Yer as daft
as your wee lad.

07:29.824 --> 07:32.624
<i>♪</i>

07:32.702 --> 07:34.952
Ooh.

07:35.080 --> 07:36.120
Well, if it’s hot,
give it back, baby.

07:36.206 --> 07:37.786
Ah, it’s broken.

07:37.874 --> 07:39.634
Jemmy.

07:39.751 --> 07:42.961
[ loud buzzing ]

07:43.088 --> 07:44.798
Can anyone else hear that?

07:44.881 --> 07:46.551
I can hear it!

07:46.633 --> 07:48.433
Dinna hear anything.

07:50.762 --> 07:53.932
[ ominous music ]

07:54.015 --> 07:55.215
Let me see this.

07:57.644 --> 07:59.314
That’s warm.

08:00.313 --> 08:01.693
It’s very warm.

08:01.815 --> 08:04.655
And a second ago,
it was hot enough to crack.

08:07.028 --> 08:08.528
Cold as stone to me.

08:11.700 --> 08:13.660
Roger.

08:13.785 --> 08:15.585
He can travel.

08:21.710 --> 08:23.790
And will ya?

08:32.429 --> 08:34.759
[ Jemmy murmuring
indistinctly ]

08:34.848 --> 08:36.348
Yeah.

08:36.474 --> 08:39.314
Come on, Jem.
Come with me.

08:39.394 --> 08:41.564
[ Jemmy whines indistinctly ]

08:41.688 --> 08:44.068
[ dramatic music ]

08:44.190 --> 08:47.240
<i>♪</i>

08:49.362 --> 08:51.782
All right, baby, just wait
here for one second.

08:51.865 --> 08:54.165
Good boy.

08:54.242 --> 08:56.332
[ horse neighs ]

09:03.877 --> 09:05.457
Well met, Mr. Fraser.

09:05.545 --> 09:09.625
Aye, I hope so, Mr. Brown.

09:09.716 --> 09:11.336
See you brought company.

09:13.303 --> 09:17.723
Mr. Fraser,
you came to me for help.

09:17.807 --> 09:19.637
Now I have come to you.

09:19.726 --> 09:22.186
<i>Now since the crown
is no longer able</i>

09:22.270 --> 09:25.270
to assure the safety
of its colonists,

09:25.398 --> 09:27.858
we must take matters
into our own hands.

09:29.569 --> 09:31.359
<i>Now we have taken it
upon ourselves</i>

09:31.446 --> 09:33.406
<i>to form a Committee of Safety</i>

09:33.490 --> 09:36.410
to protect the good folk
of Rowan County.

09:36.493 --> 09:38.663
Does the new governor
ken about this?

09:38.745 --> 09:42.165
Governor Martin can’t
officially sanction it.

09:42.248 --> 09:44.288
<i>But he knows,
and he certainly</i>

09:44.417 --> 09:46.667
<i>don’t want another uprising
on his hands.</i>

09:46.753 --> 09:49.633
You know, we’ve had word
of violent attacks.

09:49.756 --> 09:52.876
<i>Cabins burned,
families killed.</i>

09:52.967 --> 09:55.297
You have any news of such
goings‐on here at the Ridge?

09:55.428 --> 09:57.468
Aye, we have.

09:59.432 --> 10:03.482
Came across a freshly
burned cabin a few days ago.

10:03.603 --> 10:07.153
<i>Maybe ten miles
from Woolam’s Creek.</i>

10:07.273 --> 10:10.113
The dead appeared to be
a Dutch family.

10:10.235 --> 10:13.075
<i>We laid their bodies to rest.</i>

10:13.154 --> 10:15.114
That wound.

10:15.198 --> 10:17.278
<i>Looks like it needs
</i> <i>attending to.</i>

10:17.367 --> 10:19.157
Come with me into my surgery.

10:19.285 --> 10:21.745
I’ll find some clean bandages
to put on it.

10:21.830 --> 10:23.120
Well, that ain’t nothing.

10:23.248 --> 10:25.458
BROWN:
You go with her, brother.

10:25.542 --> 10:27.842
That wound’s festering
by the smell of it.

10:33.091 --> 10:35.841
[ spits ]

10:35.969 --> 10:37.849
[ inhales sharply ]

10:37.971 --> 10:39.811
How’s little Bonnie doing?

10:41.808 --> 10:44.808
I trust she’s thriving
with your niece’s family.

10:44.936 --> 10:47.056
She’s well enough.

10:47.147 --> 10:50.727
You have a nasty infection.
How long ago did you do this?

10:50.817 --> 10:52.687
A few days.

10:55.655 --> 10:58.275
I know what you think of me,
Mistress Fraser.

11:00.368 --> 11:02.368
You think I shot Morton.

11:04.372 --> 11:06.172
I’m not saying
I had a hand in that.

11:06.249 --> 11:08.579
You’re not saying
you didn’t either.

11:08.668 --> 11:10.838
You think a father’s
got no right

11:10.920 --> 11:14.010
to seek justice
for his daughter
who’s been dishonored?

11:14.132 --> 11:16.972
[ light music ]

11:17.051 --> 11:20.011
<i>♪</i>

11:22.432 --> 11:24.772
It’s gotta be the work
of the savages.

11:24.851 --> 11:27.731
We saw half a dozen cabins
burned this month.

11:27.854 --> 11:29.024
It wasna Indians.

11:30.982 --> 11:32.362
And what makes you so sure?

11:32.442 --> 11:34.442
For one thing,
no one was scalped.

11:34.527 --> 11:36.527
Even if they had been,

11:36.654 --> 11:39.994
the Indians aren’t the only
ones who take scalps.

11:40.074 --> 11:41.534
True.

11:41.659 --> 11:43.949
The white man’s learned
to take them too.

11:44.037 --> 11:47.037
Whoever it was, maybe
something scared them off.

11:48.583 --> 11:51.753
You have men
that answer to you.

11:51.878 --> 11:55.548
Will you and
your son‐in‐law join us?

11:55.632 --> 11:58.682
Ah, we have enough men
for two or three patrols.

11:58.760 --> 12:01.470
Corporal Hodgepile there
commands one group.

12:01.554 --> 12:04.974
You and your men
could form another.

12:05.058 --> 12:06.638
I appreciate the offer,

12:06.726 --> 12:08.436
but there’s a great deal
to do here.

12:08.561 --> 12:10.021
I’ll need time to consider.

12:10.104 --> 12:12.574
You might recall, Colonel,

12:12.649 --> 12:15.229
when you came to me
for men for your militia,

12:15.360 --> 12:17.490
I did not pause to consider.

12:17.570 --> 12:19.860
No, not for long.

12:21.157 --> 12:24.407
And Governor Tryon was grateful
for your timely assistance.

12:25.578 --> 12:29.078
But fighting a war
and maintaining law and order
are two different things.

12:29.207 --> 12:30.577
Your famous whiskey still

12:30.667 --> 12:33.337
needs your constant attention,
I suppose.

12:33.419 --> 12:35.379
[ chuckles ]

12:35.463 --> 12:38.473
Very well, Mr. Fraser.

12:38.591 --> 12:41.641
You think on it.

12:41.761 --> 12:43.971
You all best be vigilant.

12:44.097 --> 12:45.637
We can protect ourselves.

12:50.103 --> 12:52.483
Like I said, Mr. Brown,

12:52.605 --> 12:54.475
I’ll consider it.

12:56.609 --> 12:59.319
[ horse neighs ]

12:59.445 --> 13:00.855
Mount up!

13:00.947 --> 13:03.487
[ indistinct chatter ]

13:03.616 --> 13:06.656
[ gentle music ]

13:06.786 --> 13:09.656
<i>♪</i>

13:11.541 --> 13:13.421
Do ye really think
they’ll go then?

13:15.253 --> 13:18.633
Brianna promised Roger

13:18.715 --> 13:21.515
as soon as they knew
if Jemmy could travel.

13:28.975 --> 13:31.445
Are we going to talk
about what happened?

13:34.147 --> 13:36.187
There’s not much we can say
about the Browns.

13:36.316 --> 13:38.146
They, uh‐‐
they do as they please.

13:39.569 --> 13:41.989
Not the Browns, Uncle.

13:42.071 --> 13:43.991
The opal.

13:44.115 --> 13:46.455
<i>The Mohawk told us
that Otter Tooth’s ghost</i>

13:46.534 --> 13:49.544
appears to the one
who has the stone.

13:49.662 --> 13:52.582
You found the opal.

13:52.665 --> 13:54.245
<i>You said he appeared to you?</i>

13:54.334 --> 13:56.964
Yes.

13:57.045 --> 13:58.425
But I‐‐

13:58.504 --> 14:00.924
<i>The Mohawk think that
the one who has the stone</i>

14:01.007 --> 14:03.177
has the power to see
what will come to pass.

14:05.053 --> 14:06.893
They asked about you.

14:07.013 --> 14:09.183
<i>After ye left.</i>

14:09.307 --> 14:11.767
What did ye tell them?

14:11.851 --> 14:14.731
The truth.

14:14.854 --> 14:17.444
There isna anyone like
my Auntie Claire.

14:17.523 --> 14:21.193
<i>And ’tis true,
the way ye speak</i>

14:21.277 --> 14:23.607
<i>and medicines,</i>

14:23.696 --> 14:25.526
that you came to
Uncle Jamie so suddenly

14:25.656 --> 14:28.526
after 20 years apart.

14:28.618 --> 14:30.038
<i>And then there’s
Brianna and Roger,</i>

14:30.161 --> 14:32.581
<i>who came from...</i>

14:32.705 --> 14:34.365
I dinna ken where.

14:34.457 --> 14:36.537
<i>As I told you once,</i>

14:36.626 --> 14:38.246
<i>I learned
not to ask questions,</i>

14:38.378 --> 14:40.168
but I have some for ye now.

14:42.298 --> 14:45.588
[ gentle music ]

14:45.718 --> 14:48.428
The Mohawk said that this
belonged to Otter Tooth.

14:48.554 --> 14:50.064
<i>I can understand some,
but it’s in Latin.</i>

14:51.557 --> 14:53.307
Does it mean
anything to you?

14:53.393 --> 14:56.563
<i>♪</i>

15:01.859 --> 15:04.569
"I am.

15:04.654 --> 15:06.164
"I still exist.

15:07.698 --> 15:10.448
<i>"Did I in that place between?</i>

15:10.576 --> 15:13.746
<i>"I do not know exactly
</i> <i>when I am,</i>

15:13.830 --> 15:15.660
<i>"nor can I find out.</i>

15:15.748 --> 15:19.038
"These people
do not measure time

15:19.127 --> 15:20.877
"by any scale I know,

15:20.962 --> 15:23.592
"nor do I have the tongue
to find out.

15:26.259 --> 15:27.759
But I know I am too late."

15:36.144 --> 15:38.024
My God.

15:41.607 --> 15:43.817
He wrote
with a ballpoint pen.

15:45.319 --> 15:46.699
What’s a ballpoint pen?

15:50.074 --> 15:51.664
Who or...

15:51.784 --> 15:53.954
or what are ye?

16:07.008 --> 16:08.798
Ian, uh...

16:11.596 --> 16:14.306
I come from another time.

16:16.976 --> 16:19.806
I come from the future.

16:21.647 --> 16:23.317
200 years from now.

16:26.110 --> 16:28.360
I‐‐

16:28.488 --> 16:30.108
I knew you were
a fairy, Auntie.

16:32.450 --> 16:33.990
I’m not a fairy.

16:35.661 --> 16:39.251
Then you, Roger and Brianna‐‐

16:42.168 --> 16:43.338
It’s all of ye.

16:48.508 --> 16:50.468
And you,

16:50.551 --> 16:53.391
you ken all this time, Uncle?

16:53.513 --> 16:55.513
Not many people
would understand,

16:55.640 --> 16:57.220
so we kept it
between ourselves.

16:57.350 --> 16:59.020
Did Murtagh ken?

17:00.728 --> 17:03.108
Aye.
Aye, he did.

17:04.690 --> 17:07.190
Now so do you.

17:07.276 --> 17:09.026
[ sighs ]

17:09.153 --> 17:12.033
<i>♪</i>

17:20.206 --> 17:23.036
[ birds chirping ]

17:36.889 --> 17:38.309
You can come out.

17:44.021 --> 17:45.361
Mistress.

17:45.439 --> 17:47.569
Sir.

17:47.650 --> 17:50.400
Ulysses, how are you?

17:50.486 --> 17:52.236
I am well.

17:52.321 --> 17:53.911
Thank you, Mistress.

17:53.990 --> 17:56.740
My only complaint is uh,
boredom.

17:56.826 --> 17:59.196
Well, we brought you
some food.

17:59.287 --> 18:01.707
I thought ye might find a use
for this as well.

18:03.040 --> 18:06.460
I’ve been in places with
naught but my own thoughts
for company.

18:06.586 --> 18:08.166
It may distract you
for a bit.

18:08.254 --> 18:10.264
Thank you, sir.

18:10.381 --> 18:12.551
My own thoughts are but...

18:12.633 --> 18:14.473
poor company.

18:18.264 --> 18:20.524
There’s a, uh,

18:20.600 --> 18:23.850
Committee of Safety
roaming about.

18:23.936 --> 18:25.596
At first I was afraid they
might come looking for you,

18:25.730 --> 18:27.730
but I dinna think they heard

18:27.815 --> 18:29.315
about what happened
at River Run.

18:29.442 --> 18:30.942
Now that I’m a murderer.

18:31.027 --> 18:34.857
You had no choice
but to stop Mr. Forbes.

18:34.947 --> 18:36.447
<i>JAMIE:
You saved my auntie’s life.</i>

18:36.574 --> 18:38.124
We’re verra grateful.

18:40.786 --> 18:43.496
No one will pardon me
for killing a white man,

18:43.623 --> 18:45.253
even to save Mistress Cameron.

18:45.333 --> 18:48.003
Even so,

18:48.127 --> 18:52.007
I would do the same again
given the chance.

18:52.131 --> 18:54.301
Have you given any thought
to where you might go next?

18:56.218 --> 18:58.798
Yeah, it would be wise
to leave North Carolina.

19:01.599 --> 19:03.639
Philadelphia maybe.

19:03.768 --> 19:06.188
Quakers dinna hold wi’ slavery

19:06.312 --> 19:08.192
In fact, sir, I‐‐

19:08.314 --> 19:10.654
I’m not...

19:10.733 --> 19:13.653
exactly a‐‐a slave.

19:13.736 --> 19:15.106
What do you mean?

19:16.572 --> 19:19.372
[ birds chirping ]

19:29.043 --> 19:31.673
It’s a document
of manumission.

19:31.796 --> 19:34.666
Signed by
Jocasta Cameron and...

19:34.799 --> 19:36.549
witnessed by Gerald Forbes?

19:36.676 --> 19:39.846
Ha. Yes.

19:39.929 --> 19:42.929
That was rather ironic,
I suppose.

19:43.015 --> 19:46.185
So you’ve been a free man
all this time.

19:47.520 --> 19:48.650
Yet‐‐

19:48.729 --> 19:50.399
My mistress insisted

19:50.523 --> 19:53.533
upon manumitting me
as soon as Mr. Cameron died.

19:55.528 --> 19:59.528
I chose not to leave her.

19:59.615 --> 20:02.485
[ somber music ]

20:02.576 --> 20:05.446
<i>♪</i>

20:12.461 --> 20:13.671
Well, he’s finally...

20:13.754 --> 20:16.054
[ soft clang ]

20:16.173 --> 20:17.093
Asleep.

20:18.551 --> 20:20.511
[ whispered ]
Sorry.

20:30.229 --> 20:32.559
What do you think caused
the opal to break
when Jemmy held it?

20:37.069 --> 20:39.909
There must be something
about time traveling

20:40.030 --> 20:42.660
or time travelers
that triggers that energy.

20:42.742 --> 20:44.032
But it didn’t break
with any of us.

20:44.118 --> 20:46.328
Maybe Jem is extra sensitive

20:46.412 --> 20:48.872
because both of his parents
are time travelers.

20:50.708 --> 20:52.628
Hm.

20:58.299 --> 21:01.839
It might be proof that
he is your biological son.

21:01.927 --> 21:04.677
[ light music ]

21:04.764 --> 21:07.394
<i>♪</i>

21:07.475 --> 21:10.025
All I’ve ever wanted
was for us to be a family.

21:11.562 --> 21:13.442
And for us all to be safe.

21:13.564 --> 21:15.864
<i>And we will be.</i>

21:15.941 --> 21:18.491
Safer at least.

21:18.611 --> 21:21.111
<i>We don’t need the opal.</i>

21:21.238 --> 21:23.658
I have the rubies and the gem
that Bonnet gave you.

21:26.786 --> 21:28.076
Bree...

21:32.374 --> 21:34.844
See, it’s not just the dangers.

21:34.960 --> 21:36.670
It’s living a life
we were never meant to.

21:36.796 --> 21:39.256
I know.

21:40.633 --> 21:42.383
All right.

21:42.468 --> 21:45.968
Well, I guess we need
to figure out what we’re
gonna tell people.

21:46.096 --> 21:48.346
We can’t just go "poof."

21:48.474 --> 21:50.934
[ chuckles ]

21:51.018 --> 21:54.398
That’s exactly
what we will do, isn’t it?

21:54.480 --> 21:56.150
If things go right.

21:56.232 --> 21:57.732
Yes.

21:57.817 --> 22:00.107
But I‐I don’t just wanna
leave my parents

22:00.194 --> 22:02.614
to explain
what’s happened to us.

22:05.115 --> 22:07.365
And I wanna be able
to say bye to everyone.

22:07.493 --> 22:10.663
Aye, of course.

22:10.788 --> 22:12.998
I was thinking,

22:13.123 --> 22:15.543
we tell people I’ve got a job

22:15.668 --> 22:20.008
that doesn’t require
shooting or stabbing.

22:21.674 --> 22:23.594
You know, north somewhere.

22:23.676 --> 22:25.966
Boston.
New York.

22:26.053 --> 22:28.263
Boston would be best.

22:28.347 --> 22:31.267
People know I grew up there.

22:31.350 --> 22:35.190
We could tell them you’ll be
a university professor.

22:35.271 --> 22:38.651
Which is the truth,
just in a different century.

22:38.732 --> 22:41.612
Right.

22:41.694 --> 22:44.244
Best to stay as close
to the truth as possible.

22:44.363 --> 22:45.533
Yeah.

22:45.614 --> 22:47.414
Leave within the month?

22:52.204 --> 22:55.214
[ birds chirping ]

22:58.711 --> 23:00.051
[ clears throat ]

23:00.129 --> 23:02.669
You, uh, have a visitor, sir.

23:15.811 --> 23:17.101
<i>JAMIE: John?</i>

23:18.230 --> 23:19.560
I wasn’t expecting you.

23:22.359 --> 23:25.029
‐ Is everything all right?
‐ Quite all right.

23:25.112 --> 23:26.492
And William?

23:26.572 --> 23:29.242
He’s well.
Still at school in London.

23:29.325 --> 23:31.125
Huh.

23:31.243 --> 23:33.293
Well, come,
tell me more, but‐‐

23:33.412 --> 23:36.212
Have Mr. Bug take
his lordship’s baggage

23:36.290 --> 23:38.290
up to the guest chamber.

23:38.417 --> 23:40.287
‐ Guest chamber?
<i>‐ Aye.</i>

23:40.419 --> 23:42.049
Yeah, we just finished
the upstairs.

23:42.129 --> 23:43.959
Ye’ll be our first guest.

23:44.089 --> 23:45.799
‐ I’m honored.
‐ Ah.

23:49.386 --> 23:51.596
I heard justice was served
to Mr. Bonnet after all.

23:51.680 --> 23:54.520
It was.

23:54.600 --> 23:58.190
But, uh, not by my hand.

23:59.605 --> 24:01.575
It was Brianna’s wish.

24:01.649 --> 24:05.029
He was sentenced,
and the river took him.

24:05.110 --> 24:06.950
I’m sure she will rest easy now

24:07.029 --> 24:08.779
knowing she’ll never
see his face again.

24:08.906 --> 24:10.776
Hm.

24:22.461 --> 24:24.341
So ye’re really leaving
then, Cousin?

24:24.463 --> 24:26.303
Yes.

24:26.382 --> 24:29.552
I wish things were different,
but they aren’t.

24:29.635 --> 24:32.105
Things are going
to get worse here soon.

24:32.179 --> 24:34.179
There’s a war coming.

24:34.306 --> 24:38.056
Ye dinna have to be a‐‐
whatever you are‐‐to tell that.

24:38.143 --> 24:39.943
Anyone wi’
half an eye sees it.

24:40.020 --> 24:42.650
I’m happy for you.

24:42.773 --> 24:45.323
If it’s truly what you wish.

24:45.401 --> 24:47.821
But have you thought
that maybe if you stayed,

24:47.945 --> 24:49.575
you could change things?

24:49.655 --> 24:52.665
I’m afraid what’s coming
is a lot bigger than us.

24:54.994 --> 24:57.254
Auntie.

24:57.329 --> 24:59.159
You told me
that you and Uncle Jamie

24:59.248 --> 25:01.828
thought you might stop
Charles Stuart.

25:01.917 --> 25:05.337
Stop what you ken would be
a terrible slaughter
in the highlands.

25:05.421 --> 25:08.381
Well, we were able to prevent

25:08.507 --> 25:11.337
some of the men from Lallybroch
dying at Culloden,

25:11.468 --> 25:13.888
but we weren’t able to stop
the course of events,

25:14.013 --> 25:15.813
<i>and the battle itself.</i>

25:18.600 --> 25:19.850
Ian...

25:21.103 --> 25:23.483
it’s complicated.

25:23.564 --> 25:26.194
But there are things,
smaller things

25:26.275 --> 25:28.535
that someone might be able
to change.

25:28.610 --> 25:30.950
Something much smaller
than a war,

25:31.030 --> 25:34.070
say...

25:34.199 --> 25:37.579
something between
a man and his wife.

25:37.703 --> 25:40.463
[ gentle music ]

25:40.539 --> 25:43.169
I want to travel
through the stones.

25:44.209 --> 25:45.999
I’m sorry.

25:46.086 --> 25:47.996
That won’t work.

25:48.088 --> 25:49.378
Well, why not?

25:49.465 --> 25:52.935
We think it’s something
you’re born with.

25:53.052 --> 25:56.762
The opal, it didn’t
feel hot to you.

25:56.889 --> 25:59.179
And that’s one of the signs.

25:59.266 --> 26:00.726
<i>And you didn’t hear
</i> <i>the buzzing.</i>

26:00.851 --> 26:02.691
Then you take me.

26:02.770 --> 26:04.690
You can travel, Auntie.

26:04.772 --> 26:06.902
Take me with you,
and then you can return here.

26:08.150 --> 26:09.940
I’m sorry.

26:10.069 --> 26:12.489
<i>It’s impossible.</i>

26:14.615 --> 26:17.415
Ian, is this something to do
with why you left the Mohawk?

26:19.078 --> 26:21.078
You want to go back
in time because...

26:21.163 --> 26:23.333
Ye say I can’t go.

26:23.415 --> 26:24.915
What difference does it make?

26:25.042 --> 26:27.882
[ somber music ]

26:27.961 --> 26:30.761
<i>♪</i>

26:39.556 --> 26:43.636
Seems the time has come for me
now to return to England.

26:43.769 --> 26:45.479
<i>To Helwater.</i>

26:45.604 --> 26:48.154
Helwater?

26:48.273 --> 26:50.113
It’s been a while
since I heard that name.

26:50.234 --> 26:52.824
There’s some news,
I’m afraid.

26:52.945 --> 26:54.615
Lord Dunsany has died.

26:54.696 --> 26:56.406
I must return
to make arrangements

26:56.490 --> 26:59.410
for the care of the estate,
which is now William’s,

26:59.493 --> 27:01.243
and the care of Lady Dunsany.

27:01.328 --> 27:02.828
She has no one else.

27:02.955 --> 27:05.125
Will you send her
my condolences, John,

27:05.207 --> 27:07.127
if you think she will
value them?

27:07.251 --> 27:08.591
I know she would.

27:08.669 --> 27:10.749
And I shall tell her
when I return.

27:10.838 --> 27:13.798
But having never expected
to be here in the first place,

27:13.924 --> 27:16.514
I’m finding it surprisingly
difficult to leave.

27:16.635 --> 27:18.135
Hm.

27:18.220 --> 27:20.850
Mt. Josiah has been
an escape of sorts

27:20.973 --> 27:23.643
from the outside world
and its complications.

27:23.725 --> 27:25.845
<i>I rather enjoyed
working the land.</i>

27:25.978 --> 27:28.898
Good to get dirt
under your fingernails, hm.

27:28.981 --> 27:31.571
[ inhales sharply ]
Yeah, no doubt you’ll miss it.

27:31.650 --> 27:33.150
No doubt there are
a great many things

27:33.235 --> 27:34.995
I shall miss about being here.

27:39.616 --> 27:41.576
But William is
the ninth earl of Ellesmere,

27:41.660 --> 27:43.620
<i>and when he attains
his majority,</i>

27:43.704 --> 27:47.504
he’ll be entirely responsible
for his estates.

27:47.583 --> 27:50.503
He must learn
how to be an earl.

27:50.586 --> 27:53.546
And it is my duty
to prepare him for it.

27:53.672 --> 27:56.842
Do ye think you’ll
return to Virginia?

27:56.967 --> 27:58.047
Eventually?

27:58.177 --> 27:59.677
I believe, in time, we will.

27:59.761 --> 28:02.391
<i>I can’t imagine William
never seeing you again.</i>

28:02.514 --> 28:05.484
But it is evident that the mood
in the American colonies

28:05.559 --> 28:07.059
grows darker by the day.

28:07.186 --> 28:09.896
I hope I’m wrong, but...

28:10.022 --> 28:13.022
I feel a storm coming.

28:13.150 --> 28:15.940
I dinna think you’re wrong.

28:16.028 --> 28:18.408
I brought something for you.

28:38.550 --> 28:41.680
[ gentle music ]

28:41.762 --> 28:44.682
<i>♪</i>

28:48.143 --> 28:50.983
Such a handsome lad.
[ chuckles ]

28:51.063 --> 28:53.653
The older he gets, the more
he looks like his father.

28:56.235 --> 28:57.905
Hm.

29:04.326 --> 29:06.786
<i>CLAIRE: I’ve asked Brianna
to draw some portraits for us.</i>

29:06.912 --> 29:10.122
Of all of them,
especially Jemmy.

29:10.249 --> 29:12.829
<i>Something to remember them by.</i>

29:16.505 --> 29:19.975
That’s a braw notion,
Sassenach.

29:23.095 --> 29:26.565
I remembered you for 20 years,
<i>mo chridhe.</i>

29:26.640 --> 29:28.850
No pictures at all.
Hm.

29:30.477 --> 29:32.557
But it does help.

29:36.358 --> 29:37.438
Hm.

29:54.835 --> 29:57.675
[ gentle music ]

29:57.796 --> 30:00.716
<i>♪</i>

30:30.495 --> 30:33.115
[ sighs ]

30:33.206 --> 30:35.996
[ breathing heavily ]

30:44.051 --> 30:45.931
[ sighs ]

30:50.015 --> 30:51.605
[ owl hoots ]

30:51.683 --> 30:53.853
[ exhales deeply ]

31:02.486 --> 31:04.566
Claire?

31:04.696 --> 31:07.736
[ gentle music ]

31:07.866 --> 31:10.576
<i>♪</i>

31:14.998 --> 31:17.038
Hmm. Hm.

31:17.125 --> 31:18.705
Hm.

31:22.714 --> 31:24.344
[ softly ]
Hmm.

31:24.424 --> 31:26.094
Skin’s salty.

31:26.218 --> 31:27.718
Ye been crying, lass?

31:27.803 --> 31:29.553
No.

31:29.679 --> 31:32.179
It’s just so hot,
I’ve been sweating.

31:32.265 --> 31:34.345
Hmm.

31:34.434 --> 31:36.064
I must smell
like the White Sow.

31:36.144 --> 31:37.814
Hmm.

31:37.896 --> 31:40.396
Let me see.

31:40.524 --> 31:42.324
‐ [ inhales deeply ]
‐ [ chuckles ]

31:42.401 --> 31:44.441
Onions.

31:44.569 --> 31:46.359
Garlic.

31:46.446 --> 31:49.116
Hmm.
Something hot.

31:50.826 --> 31:52.906
‐ Peppercorns, aye.
‐ [ both chuckle ]

31:53.036 --> 31:55.116
Cloves.

31:55.247 --> 31:57.367
Something woody, huh.

31:57.457 --> 31:59.537
Toadstools.
Hm.

31:59.626 --> 32:01.586
That’s not fair.

32:01.711 --> 32:04.511
You know exactly
what we had for dinner.

32:04.589 --> 32:07.759
Vinegar, dill,

32:07.884 --> 32:10.264
and pickling cucumbers again.

32:10.387 --> 32:13.427
It’s good.
I like those.

32:13.557 --> 32:16.267
<i>Eau de femme.
Ma petite fleur.</i>

32:16.351 --> 32:18.271
Hmm?

32:18.353 --> 32:19.943
Oh, let me see.

32:20.063 --> 32:22.403
Hm.

32:22.482 --> 32:24.282
[ moans softly ]

32:24.401 --> 32:26.281
‐ Gunpowder.
‐ Mm‐hmm.

32:26.361 --> 32:28.151
[ inhales deeply ]

32:28.280 --> 32:30.110
Hay.

32:30.240 --> 32:32.120
And, uh...

32:35.537 --> 32:40.117
oh, the faintest whiff
of manure.

32:40.208 --> 32:41.958
‐ Hmm.
‐ [ chuckles ]

32:42.043 --> 32:43.923
It’s very manly.

32:45.839 --> 32:48.129
Your special perfume.

32:48.216 --> 32:51.216
Ye wanted me, and I fell
asleep without touching ye.

32:51.303 --> 32:53.143
I’m sorry, Sassenach.

32:56.141 --> 32:59.191
It’s all right.

32:59.311 --> 33:01.151
You were tired.

33:09.237 --> 33:12.197
You could have raised me
from the dead for this.

33:12.324 --> 33:14.334
[ light music ]

33:14.409 --> 33:15.869
[ moans softly ]

33:15.994 --> 33:19.584
What on earth are you doing?

33:19.664 --> 33:21.674
<i>Parfum d’amour.</i>

33:24.503 --> 33:27.303
[ breathing heavily ]

33:29.591 --> 33:31.431
Trust me, <i>mo graidh.</i>

33:31.510 --> 33:34.640
<i>♪</i>

34:03.792 --> 34:05.132
What are you doing, Sassenach?

34:05.210 --> 34:08.210
I’m checking the resolution
on this new lens

34:08.296 --> 34:10.086
Lord John brought me.

34:10.215 --> 34:11.925
Here, have a look.

34:12.050 --> 34:13.930
Hm.

34:18.723 --> 34:21.483
<i>JAMIE: Ah.
I see ’em.</i>

34:21.560 --> 34:22.690
Mm‐hmm.

34:22.769 --> 34:24.399
Wee things with tails,

34:24.521 --> 34:25.351
all swimming about.

34:25.438 --> 34:27.438
Mm.

34:27.566 --> 34:29.856
‐ Aren’t they marvelous?
‐ Hm.

34:29.943 --> 34:32.283
Aye, marvelous.
[ chuckles ]

34:32.404 --> 34:35.954
Busy wee strivers,
pushing and writhing.

34:36.074 --> 34:38.914
<i>So many of them.
</i> <i>Ah.</i>

34:38.994 --> 34:40.244
You know, when you told me
about germs,

34:40.328 --> 34:42.498
I thought they’d have wee
teeth, but these don’t.

34:42.581 --> 34:45.791
<i>Never ken they’d have such
handsomely thrashing tails.</i>

34:45.917 --> 34:48.457
Well, these particular
little beasts aren’t germs.

34:49.921 --> 34:51.261
They’re sperms.

34:51.381 --> 34:52.721
What’s that?

34:52.799 --> 34:54.719
Male reproductive cells.

34:54.801 --> 34:56.971
The thing that makes babies.

34:57.095 --> 34:59.845
‐ You mean seed?
‐ <i>Mm‐hmm.</i>

34:59.931 --> 35:02.271
Well, whose are they?

35:02.392 --> 35:04.602
They’re yours, of course.
Who else’s would they be?

35:04.686 --> 35:06.976
Well‐‐how did you get them?

35:07.105 --> 35:11.105
I woke up in custody
of them this morning.

35:12.944 --> 35:15.034
You know they can live
for up to one week

35:15.113 --> 35:18.283
when they are released
into the proper habitat.

35:21.411 --> 35:24.291
[ serene music ]

35:24.372 --> 35:27.212
<i>♪</i>

35:27.292 --> 35:29.842
<i>JAMIE: I, uh,
was coming to see you.</i>

35:36.718 --> 35:38.798
Hm.

35:55.195 --> 35:57.415
Who’s this?

35:57.489 --> 35:58.819
It’s your brother.

36:05.538 --> 36:08.208
I, um...

36:08.333 --> 36:09.923
told you I was
a prisoner of war.

36:12.504 --> 36:14.924
<i>And I worked as a groom</i>

36:15.006 --> 36:17.126
on an English estate
called Helwater.

36:18.927 --> 36:21.047
Well, that’s where
he was born.

36:22.889 --> 36:26.599
His name is William,
and, aye, your, uh‐‐

36:26.685 --> 36:29.025
your mother kens
all about him.

36:30.522 --> 36:33.862
And who is his mother?

36:33.983 --> 36:36.613
If you don’t mind
telling me, I mean.

36:36.695 --> 36:38.955
Aye, I do, but, um...

36:42.784 --> 36:44.874
I’ll tell you anyway.

36:49.207 --> 36:52.537
She was a...

36:52.627 --> 36:54.377
a daughter of the estate.

36:54.504 --> 36:57.054
Her name was Geneva Dunsany.

36:59.008 --> 37:01.968
And it wasn’t a matter
of love between us,

37:02.053 --> 37:04.313
but it was her choice,

37:04.389 --> 37:06.349
and that’s all
I’ll say about it.

37:08.768 --> 37:10.268
He looks like you.

37:10.395 --> 37:12.775
Aye.
Hm.

37:12.897 --> 37:15.897
And very much like you.

37:16.025 --> 37:18.435
Uh, where is he now?
I mean, can I see him?

37:18.570 --> 37:20.610
No, he’s in London.

37:20.739 --> 37:23.369
He does not ken I’m his father,
and he never will.

37:25.410 --> 37:30.250
He is the ninth earl
of Ellesmere.

37:32.167 --> 37:34.587
If the truth were ever found
out, his life would be ruined.

37:34.711 --> 37:36.711
Hm.

37:36.796 --> 37:38.916
The eighth earl of Ellesmere,

37:39.007 --> 37:41.007
who’s the‐ the man
who supposedly sired him,

37:41.092 --> 37:44.762
died when William was born.

37:44.846 --> 37:48.016
As did his mother.

37:48.099 --> 37:51.229
So old Lord John
married her sister,

37:51.311 --> 37:53.401
and they became
Willy’s parents.

37:55.607 --> 37:58.477
So that’s the son
Lord John has told me about.

37:58.610 --> 38:01.110
‐ Aye.
‐ Wow.

38:01.237 --> 38:02.777
Right, well, Lord John
has been a father to William

38:02.906 --> 38:04.616
since the lad
was six years old.

38:06.117 --> 38:08.867
I don’t know what to say.

38:08.953 --> 38:12.083
‐ A brother.
‐ Hm. Aye.

38:12.165 --> 38:15.795
Aye, I wanted you to ken
there was more of your blood

38:15.919 --> 38:17.999
in the world
than me and your mother.

38:19.714 --> 38:21.764
Maybe you could look for him.

38:21.841 --> 38:24.261
In books, I mean.

38:25.136 --> 38:28.256
He’d be an earl.
Might be easy to find.

38:28.348 --> 38:30.218
Yeah, I will.

38:34.145 --> 38:36.145
When will you leave?

38:40.735 --> 38:42.525
We leave in a week.

38:50.662 --> 38:55.292
After your mother left me
wi’ you in her belly...

38:57.001 --> 38:59.921
I never thought I’d see you.

39:00.004 --> 39:02.884
But I kent you were there.

39:03.007 --> 39:05.967
I was a husband
and a father,

39:06.052 --> 39:09.182
and now I’m a grandsire.

39:09.264 --> 39:11.564
And even though I may never
see any of you again...

39:14.352 --> 39:17.312
you have made my life whole.

39:25.905 --> 39:27.905
MARSALI: Leaving?

39:28.032 --> 39:29.992
Roger’s been offered
a teaching position.

39:30.076 --> 39:31.656
Up north in Boston.

39:31.744 --> 39:34.334
Boston?
That’s so far away.

39:37.041 --> 39:39.341
What are your parents
gonna do without you?

39:41.212 --> 39:45.632
What am I gonna do without you
with another bairn comin’?

39:49.053 --> 39:51.393
You’ve become like
a sister to me.

39:51.514 --> 39:53.774
I know.

39:53.892 --> 39:55.432
Leaving everyone
is going to be

39:55.560 --> 39:56.730
the hardest thing
I’ve ever done.

39:56.853 --> 39:58.563
Aye.

39:58.688 --> 40:01.268
We’ll miss you both.

40:01.399 --> 40:03.729
Come here.

40:03.818 --> 40:07.198
[ gentle music ]

40:07.280 --> 40:09.240
[ indistinct chatter ]

40:09.324 --> 40:11.914
<i>WOMAN: Me either.
</i> <i>I know.</i>

40:12.035 --> 40:13.835
<i>I’m gonna miss you.</i>

40:13.912 --> 40:16.042
<i>‐ BRIANNA: I know, I’m sorry.
</i> <i>‐ WOMAN: Be good.</i>

40:16.122 --> 40:18.372
‐ Miss you.
‐ Bye.

40:18.458 --> 40:21.378
<i>♪</i>

40:37.268 --> 40:39.058
<i>LIZZIE: I suppose I should
start saying my good‐byes</i>

40:39.145 --> 40:40.765
to everyone as well
while they’re all gathered.

40:40.855 --> 40:42.355
[ Brianna sighs ]

40:42.440 --> 40:45.690
<i>I’ll miss them
and their wee puddin’ faces.</i>

40:45.777 --> 40:48.317
Dinna ken how I’ll bear it.

40:48.446 --> 40:51.196
Germain has been
a wee angel of late.

40:51.282 --> 40:53.702
Joanie too.
Bless them.

40:53.785 --> 40:55.125
Lizzie‐‐

40:55.244 --> 40:57.164
Ah, of course
I’m looking forward to it.

40:57.288 --> 40:59.748
Although it will be colder
in Boston, will it not?

40:59.832 --> 41:02.082
Lizzie.

41:03.127 --> 41:05.667
We can’t take you with us.

41:05.797 --> 41:07.627
Oh.

41:07.715 --> 41:09.335
You’ll send for me
in a few weeks then.

41:09.467 --> 41:12.047
No.

41:12.136 --> 41:14.636
You’ll have to stay here
at Fraser’s Ridge.

41:18.851 --> 41:21.441
Why?

41:21.521 --> 41:23.521
I was with you
in your darkest time,

41:23.648 --> 41:25.688
when that beast
attacked you and‐‐

41:25.817 --> 41:27.647
and the good times as well,

41:27.777 --> 41:31.487
on your wedding day
and when Jemmy was born.

41:33.992 --> 41:36.542
You’re the one that saved me.

41:36.661 --> 41:39.871
I’m meant to be with you,
always.

41:42.458 --> 41:46.838
Lizzie, you have always
been there for me,

41:46.963 --> 41:49.303
and I am so grateful.

41:49.382 --> 41:52.222
But I need someone
to stay here

41:52.343 --> 41:54.433
and look out
for my parents for me.

41:54.512 --> 41:58.182
They need someone like you
to take care of them.

42:00.643 --> 42:04.613
Of course, I will
if that’s what you wish.

42:06.065 --> 42:07.525
[ sniffles ]

42:07.608 --> 42:10.358
Lizzie, please‐‐
please, don’t cry.

42:10.486 --> 42:12.316
I am really trying
to be brave.

42:13.364 --> 42:15.704
You are brave.

42:17.410 --> 42:20.160
You’re one of
the bravest I know.

42:23.166 --> 42:25.786
I’ll never forget you.

42:25.877 --> 42:27.877
I’ll never forget you either.

42:27.962 --> 42:30.762
[ somber music ]

42:30.882 --> 42:33.762
<i>♪</i>

42:41.392 --> 42:43.442
<i>BROWN: Fraser!</i>

42:48.191 --> 42:50.191
Mr. Brown.

42:50.276 --> 42:51.736
[ Brown groans ]

42:54.322 --> 42:55.702
My brother
sent me to tell you,

42:55.782 --> 42:58.202
the Committee of Safety
are gathering in a week.

42:58.284 --> 43:00.834
<i>He wants an answer.</i>

43:00.912 --> 43:03.372
Are you and your men with us?

43:03.456 --> 43:05.366
Tell your brother
I’ve considered.

43:06.751 --> 43:10.801
With respect, I have
to decline his invitation.

43:10.922 --> 43:13.592
<i>I’ve spent the last year
</i> <i>serving the crown.</i>

43:13.674 --> 43:16.434
It’s time to serve my family.

43:16.511 --> 43:18.681
I wish ye the best of luck,
Mr. Brown.

43:18.763 --> 43:21.643
Richard will not be best
pleased to hear that,
Mr. Fraser.

43:21.766 --> 43:23.766
I’m sorry.

43:23.851 --> 43:25.641
It’s my final word.

43:27.105 --> 43:28.775
<i>I, um‐‐</i>

43:28.856 --> 43:31.976
my wife‐‐I brought my wife
to see Mistress Fraser.

43:32.110 --> 43:34.780
<i>She’s, uh,
in need of a healer.</i>

43:34.904 --> 43:36.864
Of course.

43:36.948 --> 43:38.278
She’s in her surgery.

43:45.456 --> 43:47.456
[ groans softly ]

43:50.628 --> 43:52.548
Please.

43:55.758 --> 43:57.088
How long have you two
been married?

43:57.176 --> 43:58.966
Almost a year now.

44:02.265 --> 44:03.855
Your wrist is broken.

44:03.975 --> 44:05.775
Now how did this happen?

44:09.730 --> 44:13.690
These kind of injuries
usually happen with a fall,

44:13.818 --> 44:16.648
or if the wrist
has been twisted.

44:16.737 --> 44:19.777
Just mend it,
like you mended me.

44:21.576 --> 44:24.406
Marsali, can you
get me the splints

44:24.495 --> 44:27.705
and some strips of bandage
and the balm of Gilead?

44:27.832 --> 44:31.292
I’m going to wrap the wrist
so the bone can’t move.

44:31.377 --> 44:33.587
Now, you have to try
not to use your arm too much.

44:36.424 --> 44:39.554
Lionel, could you ask
my husband for some whiskey?

44:39.677 --> 44:41.887
I need to make a tonic
for your wife.

44:42.013 --> 44:43.853
For the pain.

44:51.439 --> 44:52.609
[ hisses ]

44:52.690 --> 44:54.360
Don’t know how I’ll chop wood

44:54.483 --> 44:57.243
and do the washing
with one hand.

44:57.361 --> 44:59.571
My husband expects
the chores to be done.

44:59.697 --> 45:01.987
Well, maybe your husband
could help you with the chores.

45:03.451 --> 45:05.161
[ chuckles ]

45:05.244 --> 45:06.914
[ groans softly ]

45:07.038 --> 45:09.958
Does he get very angry
if they’re not done?

45:10.041 --> 45:12.081
Of course.

45:12.210 --> 45:15.380
What husband wouldn’t?

45:15.463 --> 45:18.473
I have seen
your husband’s anger.

45:18.549 --> 45:20.089
Be quite frightening.

45:20.218 --> 45:22.178
He hasn’t been himself

45:22.261 --> 45:24.971
since his Alicia’s gone off.

45:25.056 --> 45:27.976
He gets sad and he drinks.

45:28.059 --> 45:30.479
He wants another babe to raise.

45:32.730 --> 45:34.230
And do you?

45:34.315 --> 45:36.945
Do you want children, Rose?

45:37.068 --> 45:38.818
That’s my duty, isn’t it?

45:40.238 --> 45:41.658
He’s a good man.

45:43.616 --> 45:45.696
A good man wouldn’t hurt you.

45:47.745 --> 45:51.075
It was my own fault, you see,
because I wouldn’t‐‐

45:51.207 --> 45:54.127
I wouldn’t lie with him.

45:54.252 --> 45:57.252
I don’t mind
what he does to me,

45:57.338 --> 45:59.008
but if he was cruel
to a babe...

46:03.135 --> 46:06.675
Dr. Rawlings says that
if you don’t lie with a man

46:06.764 --> 46:08.724
two weeks before your courses,

46:08.808 --> 46:10.388
then you won’t
come to be with child.

46:10.476 --> 46:13.516
Said so in the newspaper.

46:13.604 --> 46:15.524
My mother taught me to read.

46:17.566 --> 46:18.936
Everything well in here?

46:19.068 --> 46:21.238
Very well indeed.

46:21.320 --> 46:22.950
Mistress Fraser’s
almost finished.

46:23.072 --> 46:24.872
CLAIRE: Mm‐hmm.

46:26.534 --> 46:29.334
[ suspenseful music ]

46:29.453 --> 46:32.503
<i>♪</i>

46:37.628 --> 46:39.628
All right, come on.

46:41.632 --> 46:43.682
[ groans softly ]

46:45.511 --> 46:47.471
I’m obliged to you.

46:51.684 --> 46:53.484
<i>You needn’t bother
with your tonic.</i>

46:53.602 --> 46:55.772
‐ [ door opens ]
‐ You take care, Rose.

47:05.656 --> 47:07.736
[ dog barking ]

47:20.921 --> 47:23.381
I want to, uh‐‐

47:23.507 --> 47:26.257
well, Brianna and I want
to ask a favor of you.

47:26.344 --> 47:27.764
Aye.

47:27.845 --> 47:30.595
Of course.
Whatever it is.

47:30.681 --> 47:33.061
Will ye come with us?

47:33.184 --> 47:36.024
To the stone circle, I mean.

47:36.145 --> 47:38.525
Someone will need to bring
the wagon and horses home,

47:38.606 --> 47:41.226
and we‐‐we don’t want
Jamie and Claire to do it.

47:41.359 --> 47:42.939
Why not?

47:43.027 --> 47:45.487
Brianna’s afraid that
if her parents are there

47:45.571 --> 47:47.491
she might not find
the courage to leave them.

47:50.201 --> 47:51.871
I’ll come with you.

47:53.537 --> 47:55.037
Thank you.

47:57.291 --> 48:00.091
[ bird sings ]

48:02.213 --> 48:04.553
I want you to have this.

48:04.673 --> 48:08.683
For everything that
you’ve done to help us.

48:23.275 --> 48:25.525
Can’t except your land.

48:25.611 --> 48:27.741
Then look after it for me.

48:30.658 --> 48:32.738
And do with it what you will.

48:35.162 --> 48:37.002
I hope you find happiness.

48:37.081 --> 48:39.921
[ light music ]

48:40.042 --> 48:42.962
<i>♪</i>

48:44.755 --> 48:47.585
[ chickens cluck ]

48:59.437 --> 49:02.147
Your father tells me you
and Roger are going to Boston.

49:02.273 --> 49:04.193
Yes.

49:05.943 --> 49:07.493
And I’ve just learned something
that’s gonna make it

49:07.611 --> 49:10.111
even harder to leave.

49:10.239 --> 49:11.739
I have a brother.

49:11.824 --> 49:14.284
Yeah.

49:14.368 --> 49:15.868
So he’s told you.

49:19.206 --> 49:21.166
I’m glad.

49:21.292 --> 49:23.172
He’s very much like you.

49:23.294 --> 49:27.264
And both of you are
very much like your father.

49:27.339 --> 49:28.969
Both in appearance
and disposition.

49:29.091 --> 49:30.301
Hm.

49:30.426 --> 49:31.546
So William has
a temper too then?

49:31.635 --> 49:33.215
Yes.
[ chuckles ]

49:33.304 --> 49:35.474
Yes, he does.

49:35.598 --> 49:37.308
He possesses your kindness
and courage.

49:37.391 --> 49:39.311
Jamie’s as well.

49:41.854 --> 49:44.314
I can never tell him
about you.

49:46.150 --> 49:47.990
Though I wish I could.

49:49.361 --> 49:50.991
But...

49:51.113 --> 49:53.783
I know.

49:53.866 --> 49:56.076
‐ [ sighs ]
‐ My father explained.

49:56.827 --> 50:00.457
Well, life is long.

50:00.539 --> 50:02.419
Perhaps someday.

50:02.500 --> 50:05.090
Perhaps.

50:05.169 --> 50:06.999
I’ll be leaving myself
in two days’ time.

50:08.631 --> 50:10.671
With my new manservant.

50:10.799 --> 50:12.969
‐ Your manservant.
‐ Ulysses.

50:13.052 --> 50:15.102
Taking him
to England with you?

50:15.179 --> 50:17.509
He can travel safely
in the guise of my servant.

50:17.640 --> 50:19.600
When he sets foot
on a British ship,

50:19.683 --> 50:21.353
he’ll be a free man.

50:21.477 --> 50:22.847
That’s a good idea.

50:22.937 --> 50:25.357
Your father thought of it.

50:25.439 --> 50:26.859
[ chuckles ]

50:26.941 --> 50:28.941
He reminded me that
I might need someone

50:29.026 --> 50:31.276
to play chess with
on the long voyage to London.

50:31.362 --> 50:33.412
I have heard that you’re
quite the master at chess.

50:33.531 --> 50:35.821
[ both chuckle ]

50:35.908 --> 50:38.698
And a wonderful father.

50:38.827 --> 50:40.827
My brother’s lucky
to have you in his life.

50:42.039 --> 50:44.419
And so am I.

50:44.542 --> 50:48.212
You really are
impossible not to like.

50:48.337 --> 50:50.207
[ chuckles ]

50:51.423 --> 50:54.263
[ indistinct chatter ]

50:54.385 --> 50:57.225
[ light music ]

50:57.304 --> 51:00.224
<i>♪</i>

51:12.069 --> 51:14.149
I never had grandparents.

51:15.823 --> 51:18.583
Neither did I.

51:18.701 --> 51:20.411
Not even parents
to begin with.

51:37.761 --> 51:40.601
<i>♪</i>

51:40.681 --> 51:42.721
Mama.

51:42.808 --> 51:45.638
[ sweeping dramatic music ]

51:45.769 --> 51:48.809
<i>♪</i>

51:57.823 --> 52:00.413
[ owl hoots ]

52:01.035 --> 52:04.125
Now, I thought before dinner,

52:04.204 --> 52:08.084
we could have the future’s
answer to journey cake,

52:08.167 --> 52:10.497
peanut butter
and jelly sandwiches.

52:10.628 --> 52:13.418
[ gentle string music ]

52:13.505 --> 52:16.125
<i>♪</i>

52:16.258 --> 52:17.468
Hm.

52:34.026 --> 52:36.276
<i>JAMIE: Very tasty, but, um...</i>

52:38.155 --> 52:40.025
are you sure it’s to be eaten?

52:40.157 --> 52:42.077
Ye could seal letters or mend
your boots wi’ it as well.

52:42.159 --> 52:45.369
[ laughter ]

52:48.707 --> 52:50.787
[ Claire sighs ]

52:53.504 --> 52:56.094
To home.

52:56.173 --> 52:57.303
To family.

52:57.383 --> 52:59.843
<i>Great health.</i>

52:59.968 --> 53:01.928
‐ JAMIE: Slàinte mhath.
<i>‐ Slàinte mhath.</i>

53:02.012 --> 53:04.012
ALL: <i>Slàinte mhath.</i>

53:04.098 --> 53:07.018
<i>♪</i>

53:11.772 --> 53:14.482
[ gentle music continues ]

53:14.566 --> 53:17.526
<i>♪</i>

53:55.107 --> 53:58.277
[ Jemmy talking indistinctly ]

53:58.402 --> 54:01.402
Up here, Dad.

54:01.488 --> 54:04.118
Are we going for a walk?

54:10.497 --> 54:13.377
<i>♪</i>

54:19.965 --> 54:24.585
[ buzzing, whistling ]

54:34.772 --> 54:36.272
[ Jemmy whispers indistinctly ]

54:38.400 --> 54:41.650
[ whining ]
Mommy, [indistinct].

54:57.044 --> 54:59.304
Thought I might find you here.

55:03.675 --> 55:06.045
It’s only been two weeks.

55:06.136 --> 55:08.596
Feels like they’ve been gone
for an eternity.

55:08.680 --> 55:11.020
Yeah.

55:14.144 --> 55:16.154
And if Roger was right,

55:16.230 --> 55:19.230
they should be reaching the
stone circle right about now.

55:20.901 --> 55:23.741
[ gentle music ]

55:23.821 --> 55:26.991
<i>♪</i>

55:28.534 --> 55:31.084
We started our life
on the Ridge in this cabin.

55:33.455 --> 55:35.325
And now it’s just
you and me again.

55:38.502 --> 55:40.462
Hm.

55:42.339 --> 55:44.589
We’re not alone, Sassenach.

55:54.351 --> 55:56.271
Hm?

55:59.648 --> 56:01.858
She’s so talented.

56:01.942 --> 56:03.652
Aye.

56:03.735 --> 56:07.525
Maybe in the future she can
finally be an engineer.

56:11.577 --> 56:14.447
[ buzzing ]

56:17.040 --> 56:18.880
Are ye ready?

56:19.001 --> 56:20.541
Mm‐hmm.

56:20.627 --> 56:23.207
Mm‐hmm.

56:23.338 --> 56:25.588
‐ As we’ll ever be.
‐ [ talking indistinctly ]

56:27.301 --> 56:30.181
Each strand of this rope
is delicate and fragile.

56:32.389 --> 56:35.099
But braided together,
it’s strong,

56:35.225 --> 56:37.225
and it’ll hold us.

56:38.937 --> 56:40.557
Let’s hope so.

56:42.983 --> 56:45.243
Ian.

56:45.319 --> 56:47.399
Thank you for everything
you’ve done for us.

56:49.114 --> 56:50.534
<i>Take care of my parents.</i>

56:51.408 --> 56:52.578
I love you.

56:52.659 --> 56:55.199
I love you too, cousin.

56:56.580 --> 56:58.160
Ooh.
[ chuckles ]

57:00.417 --> 57:03.167
Here.

57:03.253 --> 57:06.883
Jem, baby, take that one.

57:06.965 --> 57:09.005
Hold it tight, okay?

57:09.092 --> 57:10.392
‐ I will.
‐ Hold it tight.

57:10.469 --> 57:13.099
‐ I’m holding it tight.
‐ Yeah, good boy.

57:13.180 --> 57:15.100
[ buzzing and whistling ]

57:15.182 --> 57:17.982
[ dramatic music ]

57:18.101 --> 57:21.191
<i>♪</i>

57:26.944 --> 57:27.944
[ buzzing and whistling stops ]

57:28.028 --> 57:30.818
[ birds chirping ]

57:30.948 --> 57:33.738
[ breathing heavily ]

57:45.128 --> 57:48.008
[ somber music ]

57:48.131 --> 57:51.181
<i>♪</i>

57:53.887 --> 57:56.717
[ wind whistling ]

57:57.975 --> 57:59.145
I’m okay!

58:00.769 --> 58:02.229
[ indistinct ]

58:02.312 --> 58:04.442
Are you all right?

58:04.523 --> 58:06.943
I just feel like
I’ve been turned inside out.

58:07.025 --> 58:08.815
‐ Mommy.
‐ Jem.

58:08.902 --> 58:11.782
‐ [ indistinct ]
‐ We made it.

58:11.863 --> 58:14.073
Aye.

58:14.157 --> 58:17.157
[ chattering indistinctly ]

58:22.916 --> 58:25.456
What the devil?

58:27.087 --> 58:28.337
What do you think?

58:28.422 --> 58:30.762
What a privilege to help
with such a task.

58:30.841 --> 58:32.681
‐ JAMIE: Hm.
‐ RONNIE: Aye.

58:32.759 --> 58:36.599
You may laugh,
but there’s an art to it.

58:36.680 --> 58:39.770
Voltaire says the perfect
is the enemy of the good.

58:39.850 --> 58:42.690
I’m sure Voltaire never dug
a privy in his life.

58:42.811 --> 58:45.521
[ loud boom ]

58:45.647 --> 58:47.517
Fire?

58:49.276 --> 58:51.106
The still.

58:51.194 --> 58:54.074
[ tense music ]

58:54.197 --> 58:55.487
<i>♪</i>

58:55.574 --> 58:57.874
‐ CLAIRE: What was that?
‐ The still.

58:57.993 --> 58:59.123
Well, I’m coming with you.

58:59.202 --> 59:01.002
No, no, no, you have
patients to attend to.

59:01.079 --> 59:03.749
We’ll see to them.

59:03.874 --> 59:07.004
CLAIRE: The trick is
to get the humerus bone,

59:07.085 --> 59:09.085
which is the upper arm bone,

59:09.212 --> 59:12.012
‐ into the right angle...
‐ [ groaning ]

59:12.090 --> 59:15.010
So that when you apply force,

59:15.093 --> 59:16.593
the head of the bone will‐‐

59:16.720 --> 59:19.560
[ yelling ]

59:19.639 --> 59:22.059
Back into the shoulder joint.

59:22.184 --> 59:24.774
Aye, sort of like
the opposite of what you do

59:24.895 --> 59:27.735
when ya joint a hog.

59:27.814 --> 59:30.114
Yes, well, in that case you’re
cutting everything apart.

59:30.233 --> 59:31.733
Here, we’re putting it
back together.

59:31.818 --> 59:33.068
Hmm.

59:33.195 --> 59:35.245
Well, thank God
for small mercies, eh?

59:35.363 --> 59:37.453
‐ [ clattering ]
‐ What on earth?

59:37.574 --> 59:39.284
What’s the meaning of this?

59:39.409 --> 59:40.989
[ groans ]
No!

59:41.078 --> 59:43.408
Hide, stay there
no matter what happens.

59:43.538 --> 59:45.368
[ grunting ]
No! Get off of me!

59:45.457 --> 59:46.997
GEORDIE:
Let her go, you bastards‐‐

59:47.084 --> 59:48.334
[ Claire groaning ]

59:48.418 --> 59:50.418
GEORDIE: Get outta here!
[ groans ]

59:50.504 --> 59:51.924
CLAIRE: Let go of me!

59:52.047 --> 59:55.257
[ grunting ]

59:55.383 --> 59:56.803
‐ CLAIRE: Marsali!
‐ [ screams ]

59:56.927 --> 59:58.427
<i>CLAIRE: No!</i>

59:58.512 --> 1:00:00.602
‐ [ grunting ]
‐ No!

1:00:00.680 --> 1:00:03.140
Jamie! No!

1:00:03.266 --> 1:00:04.846
<i>Jamie!</i>

1:00:15.237 --> 1:00:17.947
Germain.

1:00:18.073 --> 1:00:19.993
It’s nearly dark.

1:00:20.117 --> 1:00:21.827
What‐what are you doing?

1:00:21.952 --> 1:00:24.452
What are you doing out here
by yourself, <i>p’tit garçon?</i>

1:00:24.579 --> 1:00:27.919
‐ Where’s Mama?
‐ Mama won’t wake up, Papa.

1:00:29.084 --> 1:00:30.214
Where’s your grannie?

1:00:30.293 --> 1:00:33.213
[ whispered ]
The bad men took Grandmama.

1:00:33.296 --> 1:00:36.166
[ tense music ]

1:00:36.299 --> 1:00:39.339
<i>♪</i>

1:00:44.975 --> 1:00:46.065
Sh‐she’s breathing.

1:00:46.143 --> 1:00:47.853
Claire?

1:00:49.146 --> 1:00:50.356
<i>Claire?</i>

1:00:50.480 --> 1:00:52.650
[ birds caw ]

1:00:53.650 --> 1:00:54.980
<i>Claire?</i>

1:00:55.068 --> 1:00:57.858
[ dramatic music ]

1:00:57.988 --> 1:01:00.868
<i>♪</i>

